1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:03,871
If your team already uses Playwright, the hard part is not

2
00:00:03,871 --> 00:00:07,242
believing that automated tests matter.

3
00:00:07,242 --> 00:00:10,613
The hard part is writing enough useful coverage without spending

4
00:00:10,613 --> 00:00:13,983
every sprint inside selectors, waits, setup code, and flaky

5
00:00:13,983 --> 00:00:17,354
failures.

6
00:00:17,354 --> 00:00:20,725
Quorvex AI is built around one practical idea: let agents help

7
00:00:20,725 --> 00:00:24,096
create and validate tests, but keep the final output as normal

8
00:00:24,096 --> 00:00:27,467
Playwright code your team can inspect, commit, and run in CI.

9
00:00:27,467 --> 00:00:30,838
In this tutorial, I will show the first workflow end to end.

10
00:00:30,838 --> 00:00:34,209
We will start from the repo, open the dashboard, describe a

11
00:00:34,209 --> 00:00:37,579
small test in plain English, run it through the pipeline, and

12
00:00:37,579 --> 00:00:40,950
inspect the generated Playwright file.

13
00:00:40,950 --> 00:00:44,321
The point is not to watch a polished demo and assume everything

14
00:00:44,321 --> 00:00:47,692
is automatic.

15
00:00:47,692 --> 00:00:51,063
The point is to understand the loop: write a clear spec, let

16
00:00:51,063 --> 00:00:54,434
Quorvex plan against the target, generate a test, validate it in

17
00:00:54,434 --> 00:00:57,805
a browser, and then review the output like engineering work.

18
00:00:57,805 --> 00:01:01,175
Start on the GitHub repo.

19
00:01:01,175 --> 00:01:04,546
The README gives the product shape: Quorvex is self-hosted,

20
00:01:04,546 --> 00:01:07,917
AI-assisted, and code-first.

21
00:01:07,917 --> 00:01:11,288
It can work with specs, PRDs, exploration, API checks, load

22
00:01:11,288 --> 00:01:14,659
tests, security checks, database checks, CI gates, and

23
00:01:14,659 --> 00:01:18,030
autonomous coverage discovery, but the first video should stay

24
00:01:18,030 --> 00:01:21,401
narrow.

25
00:01:21,401 --> 00:01:24,772
The fastest path is the minimal setup.

26
00:01:24,772 --> 00:01:28,142
For a local evaluation, it keeps the number of services low

27
00:01:28,142 --> 00:01:31,513
while still showing the real dashboard and generation flow.

28
00:01:31,513 --> 00:01:34,884
For production or team usage, Quorvex also supports the full

29
00:01:34,884 --> 00:01:38,255
stack with queues, storage, browser viewing, credentials,

30
00:01:38,255 --> 00:01:41,626
schedules, and integrations.

31
00:01:41,626 --> 00:01:44,997
If you want the quickest trial, use the minimal README.

32
00:01:44,997 --> 00:01:48,368
If you want to evaluate the full platform shape, use the main

33
00:01:48,368 --> 00:01:51,738
getting-started tutorial.

34
00:01:51,738 --> 00:01:55,109
Either way, the first target is simple: get the backend and

35
00:01:55,109 --> 00:01:58,480
dashboard running, then generate one test.

36
00:01:58,480 --> 00:02:01,851
Before adding credentials, pause on the model configuration.

37
00:02:01,851 --> 00:02:05,222
Quorvex uses an Anthropic-compatible setup.

38
00:02:05,222 --> 00:02:08,593
That can point to Anthropic, OpenRouter, Z.ai, or another

39
00:02:08,593 --> 00:02:11,964
compatible endpoint, depending on how you run it.

40
00:02:11,964 --> 00:02:15,334
The exact provider matters less than having a working token and

41
00:02:15,334 --> 00:02:18,705
a model that can follow the generation workflow.

42
00:02:18,705 --> 00:02:22,076
Once the app is running, open the dashboard.

43
00:02:22,076 --> 00:02:25,447
The dashboard is not just decoration around a CLI.

44
00:02:25,447 --> 00:02:28,818
It is where a team can create specs, inspect runs, review

45
00:02:28,818 --> 00:02:32,189
artifacts, track requirements, see regression history, and

46
00:02:32,189 --> 00:02:35,560
understand what the agents did.

47
00:02:35,560 --> 00:02:38,930
For the first video, keep the dashboard tour brief.

48
00:02:38,930 --> 00:02:42,301
We only need enough context to create or run a spec.

49
00:02:42,301 --> 00:02:45,672
Later videos can go deeper into requirements, API testing, PRDs,

50
00:02:45,672 --> 00:02:49,043
autonomous missions, and CI quality gates.

51
00:02:49,043 --> 00:02:52,414
Now move to the most important object in the first workflow: the

52
00:02:52,414 --> 00:02:55,785
spec.

53
00:02:55,785 --> 00:02:59,156
A Quorvex spec is just markdown.

54
00:02:59,156 --> 00:03:02,526
It names the test, describes the steps, and states the expected

55
00:03:02,526 --> 00:03:05,897
outcome.

56
00:03:05,897 --> 00:03:09,268
That makes the request reviewable before any code is generated.

57
00:03:09,268 --> 00:03:12,639
This is an important design choice.

58
00:03:12,639 --> 00:03:16,010
If the input is vague, the generated code will probably be vague

59
00:03:16,010 --> 00:03:19,381
too.

60
00:03:19,381 --> 00:03:22,752
A good spec gives the agent a clear target URL, a small user

61
00:03:22,752 --> 00:03:26,123
flow, and an observable outcome.

62
00:03:26,123 --> 00:03:29,493
For the first run, use a simple public page or one workflow in

63
00:03:29,493 --> 00:03:32,864
your own application.

64
00:03:32,864 --> 00:03:36,235
Keep it small.

65
00:03:36,235 --> 00:03:39,606
A good first test proves the pipeline and gives you generated

66
00:03:39,606 --> 00:03:42,977
code that is easy to inspect.

67
00:03:42,977 --> 00:03:46,348
In the getting-started tutorial, the example checks a dynamic

68
00:03:46,348 --> 00:03:49,719
loading page and verifies that the Hello World message appears

69
00:03:49,719 --> 00:03:53,089
after the loading step completes.

70
00:03:53,089 --> 00:03:56,460
That is not a business-critical workflow, but it is a good first

71
00:03:56,460 --> 00:03:59,831
proof because the expected result is easy to see.

72
00:03:59,831 --> 00:04:03,202
After the spec is ready, run the pipeline.

73
00:04:03,202 --> 00:04:06,573
Under the hood, Quorvex is not trying to give you a cute code

74
00:04:06,573 --> 00:04:09,944
snippet.

75
00:04:09,944 --> 00:04:13,315
The workflow is planning, generation, validation, and repair

76
00:04:13,315 --> 00:04:16,685
attempts when failures are concrete enough to address.

77
00:04:16,685 --> 00:04:20,056
Planning matters because web tests need sequencing.

78
00:04:20,056 --> 00:04:23,427
The agent has to understand where to navigate, what to click,

79
00:04:23,427 --> 00:04:26,798
what to wait for, and what assertion proves the flow worked.

80
00:04:26,798 --> 00:04:30,169
Browser context matters because selectors are not reliable when

81
00:04:30,169 --> 00:04:33,540
they are guessed from a prompt alone.

82
00:04:33,540 --> 00:04:36,911
A real browser gives the system evidence about what is actually

83
00:04:36,911 --> 00:04:40,281
on the page.

84
00:04:40,281 --> 00:04:43,652
Generation matters because the output should be standard

85
00:04:43,652 --> 00:04:47,023
Playwright TypeScript.

86
00:04:47,023 --> 00:04:50,394
This is the key ownership point.

87
00:04:50,394 --> 00:04:53,765
You should be able to open the file, read it, edit it, commit

88
00:04:53,765 --> 00:04:57,136
it, and run it without Quorvex sitting in the middle of every

89
00:04:57,136 --> 00:05:00,507
future CI job.

90
00:05:00,507 --> 00:05:03,877
Validation matters because generated code is only useful after

91
00:05:03,877 --> 00:05:07,248
it runs.

92
00:05:07,248 --> 00:05:10,619
A failing generated test is not worthless, but it is not done.

93
00:05:10,619 --> 00:05:13,990
The run artifacts tell you whether the failure is in the target

94
00:05:13,990 --> 00:05:17,361
app, the spec, timing, selectors, authentication, or the

95
00:05:17,361 --> 00:05:20,732
generated code itself.

96
00:05:20,732 --> 00:05:24,103
When the run completes, do not just look for a green status.

97
00:05:24,103 --> 00:05:27,474
Open the generated file.

98
00:05:27,474 --> 00:05:30,844
Check the locators.

99
00:05:30,844 --> 00:05:34,215
Check the assertions.

100
00:05:34,215 --> 00:05:37,586
Check whether the code reads like something you would accept in

101
00:05:37,586 --> 00:05:40,957
a pull request.

102
00:05:40,957 --> 00:05:44,328
This review habit is what separates useful AI automation from

103
00:05:44,328 --> 00:05:47,699
throwaway demos.

104
00:05:47,699 --> 00:05:51,070
If the test is readable and the assertion is meaningful, the

105
00:05:51,070 --> 00:05:54,440
generated file can become part of the suite.

106
00:05:54,440 --> 00:05:57,811
If it is too broad, too brittle, or too clever, edit it or

107
00:05:57,811 --> 00:06:01,182
improve the spec and run again.

108
00:06:01,182 --> 00:06:04,553
If validation fails, the run artifacts still matter.

109
00:06:04,553 --> 00:06:07,924
Screenshots, logs, browser evidence, and failure details make

110
00:06:07,924 --> 00:06:11,295
the problem concrete.

111
00:06:11,295 --> 00:06:14,666
The goal is not magic.

112
00:06:14,666 --> 00:06:18,036
The goal is a faster loop with evidence.

113
00:06:18,036 --> 00:06:21,407
In a real team, this also changes the review conversation.

114
00:06:21,407 --> 00:06:24,778
Instead of asking whether AI wrote a perfect test, the better

115
00:06:24,778 --> 00:06:28,149
question is whether the system produced a useful candidate with

116
00:06:28,149 --> 00:06:31,520
enough evidence for an engineer or QA automation owner to make a

117
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:34,891
decision.

118
00:06:34,891 --> 00:06:38,262
This workflow is why Quorvex is self-hosted and code-first.

119
00:06:38,262 --> 00:06:41,632
AI helps with planning, generation, validation, exploration, and

120
00:06:41,632 --> 00:06:45,003
repair, but your team keeps normal tests that can run without an

121
00:06:45,003 --> 00:06:48,374
AI dependency during every CI job.

122
00:06:48,374 --> 00:06:51,745
That also means you can start small.

123
00:06:51,745 --> 00:06:55,116
You do not need to migrate a whole test suite.

124
00:06:55,116 --> 00:06:58,487
Pick one flow with clear value.

125
00:06:58,487 --> 00:07:01,858
Generate one test.

126
00:07:01,858 --> 00:07:05,228
Review the output.

127
00:07:05,228 --> 00:07:08,599
Run it locally.

128
00:07:08,599 --> 00:07:11,970
Then decide whether the next workflow should be another UI test,

129
00:07:11,970 --> 00:07:15,341
an API check, a PRD-to-tests flow, or a CI gate.

130
00:07:15,341 --> 00:07:18,712
If you are evaluating Quorvex for a team, I would measure three

131
00:07:18,712 --> 00:07:22,083
things after this first run.

132
00:07:22,083 --> 00:07:25,454
First, did it save time compared with writing the same

133
00:07:25,454 --> 00:07:28,825
Playwright test by hand?

134
00:07:28,825 --> 00:07:32,195
Second, is the generated code readable enough to maintain?

135
00:07:32,195 --> 00:07:35,566
Third, did the artifacts explain what happened when the run

136
00:07:35,566 --> 00:07:38,937
passed or failed?

137
00:07:38,937 --> 00:07:42,308
If the answer is no, the feedback is still useful.

138
00:07:42,308 --> 00:07:45,679
It tells us whether the spec format needs better guidance,

139
00:07:45,679 --> 00:07:49,050
whether the dashboard needs clearer evidence, or whether the

140
00:07:49,050 --> 00:07:52,421
generation pipeline needs a stronger constraint.

141
00:07:52,421 --> 00:07:55,791
To try this yourself, open the repo, follow the minimal setup,

142
00:07:55,791 --> 00:07:59,162
and create one spec from a real workflow your team cares about.

143
00:07:59,162 --> 00:08:02,533
If that first generated test is useful, the next step is to add

144
00:08:02,533 --> 00:08:05,904
PRD coverage, API checks, regression batches, and CI quality

145
00:08:05,904 --> 00:08:09,275
gates.

146
00:08:09,275 --> 00:08:12,646
The repo is https://github.com/NihadMemmedli/quorvex_ai, and the

147
00:08:12,646 --> 00:08:16,017
docs are at https://nihadmemmedli.github.io/quorvex_ai/.

148
00:08:16,017 --> 00:08:19,387
Star Quorvex AI if you want to follow the project, and send

149
00:08:19,387 --> 00:08:22,758
feedback from real Playwright workflows.

150
00:08:22,758 --> 00:08:26,129
That feedback is the most useful signal for what to improve

151
00:08:26,129 --> 00:08:29,500
next.
